		<div class="post" id="post-2726386">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2726386)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2726386">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2000367&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610163605" alt="WrongJohnSilver" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2000367)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;" >WrongJohnSilver</a></span> <span class="odate time_1484405897 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">14 Jan 2017 14:58</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2726386">
									

<p>Although second person viewpoints are rare in literature as a whole, it's rather facile to claim that it puts it into the realm of the &quot;dime store choose your own adventure books&quot;. A number of other stories on this site also use the second person, and have done well for themselves.</p>
<p>Certainly, given the writing on the surface, would you say that it would be improved by replacing the second person with the first or third person? That, I'm not convinced of.</p>
<p>Use of the second person does contain a certain hubris inherent in the piece by daring to say the reader contains qualities of the main character in the narrative. However, most writers are looking to create a main character that the reader can relate to in some way, anyway; the second person is simply one tool in that context. It's a bit of a punch to the gut, but not so different from filming a short completely from a character's POV.</p>
<p>Is it that punch you're disapproving of?</p>

							</div>

								
					
